Inflation in Europe has slipped on food
Accelerated inflation, measured in the euro area, is mainly due to the rapid rise in food prices.
In November, the increase in prices in the 13 countries of the euro area was higher than expected, after an inflation rate of 2.6 percent in October, an annual inflation of 3.1 percent was recorded, said the European Community statistics office located in Luxembourg.
Official forecasts showed only 3 percent, Bloomberg said.
Unlike the U.S., British and Canadian central banks, the European Central Bank (ECB) has not lowered the key interest rate by saying that lower interest rates, along with rising commodity prices and falling unemployment rates, would lead to the generation of an inflationary spiral.
The ECB would like to keep the inflation rate below but close to two percent.
According to one analyst, it is Catch 22 for the ECB: "we must deter" inflation so that we do not have to intervene on this subject later.
In Germany, the inflation rate of 3.3 per cent is a record over the past twelve years and in Spain it has risen from 3.6 to 4.1.
Inflation in the euro area has picked up because of the rapid rise in food and energy prices.
The futures market rates of cereals have increased by 88 percent and the price of soybeans has also reached its highest value since 1973.
The price of food oil and dairy products also increased significantly in 2007.
This year, the world price of oil rose by 52 percent, and last month, a barrel of black gold cost almost $100.
According to the ECB, in 2008 the inflation rate will rise from 2.1 to 2.5 per cent this year, but in 2009 it will drop to 1.9 per cent.
According to analysts, the 12-month inflation rate remains around 3 percent, however, for the next 3-4 months, the average annual rate will be 2.1 percent.
At the same time, they expect the ECB to cut the policy rate twice in 2008.
Gallup Reports Government Crisis
After a long stagnation, the number of supporters of Fidesz (Alliance of Young Democrats) increased significantly at the beginning of December. Thus, since 2002, it currently has the highest number of supporters, while Gallup (Survey Institute) has never before seen such low socialist support, namely 13 percent.
For loyal voters, the difference would represent, due to the greater determination of the opposition voters, a support of more than two-thirds (71 percent) against the support of a fifth (20 percent) for the MSZP (Hungarian Socialist Party).
According to the poll, the MDF (Forum of Hungarian Democrats) and the SZDSZ (Alliance of Free Democrats) are below the threshold of parliamentarians: their support is two percent across the population.
Of the loyal voters certain to go to vote, the number of supporters of the two parties increased by 1 percent.
The economic climate has continued to deteriorate from the previous lowest point, the proportion of those who considered the economic situation of the country to be particularly serious has never been higher, it rises to 41 per cent and according to 46 per cent the situation is quite serious.
After the more optimistic outlook for spring and summer last year, families are once again more pessimistic about their financial situation.
For next year, the majority of the population expects a worsening and only one-tenth of the population expects an improvement.
Last December, 71 percent of those polled, a majority never seen in Gallup’s previous polls, said the prime minister was doing his job rather badly than well.
13 percent of respondents have confidence or a lot of confidence in Ferenc Gyurcsány while 38 percent support Viktor Orbán.
54 percent do not trust the prime minister at all and 27 percent do not trust the president of Fidesz.
One of the indicators of change in the political situation is the proportion of society that believes that discontent with the Prime Minister can be dealt with without a change of government.
While after the riots last October, 35 percent of respondents wanted the government and the Prime Minister to remain in office, currently this rate is only 20 percent. The relative majority (33 percent) believe that holding new elections would be the solution to this situation.
When asked about the intent to vote, 60 percent of respondents said they would certainly vote and the additional 20 percent said they would probably vote.
For comparison, for a "legislative election to hold next Sunday", only 55 percent of the respondents would certainly participate and 15 percent more would probably participate. According to current intentions, the result of the referendum would not be in doubt.
74 per cent of people would say no to higher education fees, 79 per cent would say no to consultation fees, and 84 per cent would say no to hospital fees.
When we look at only the same proportions among those who expressed their intention to vote in the referendum, respectively, 81, 84 and 89 percent of voters would reject the introduction of registration fees, consultation fees and hospital living expenses.
Auchan is the most expensive, Tesco has increased its prices by almost twenty percent
The hypermarkets in the Budaörs commercial triangle maintained last year's average price increase of 16 percent, with the difference that this year's VAT rate has not increased.
Article by Napi Gazdaság (Daily Economy)
This year, in the commercial triangle of Budaörs, the usual daily Christmas Basket also increased by 16 percent on average, with a value increase of well over a thousand forints showing up in all hypermarkets.
Prices, which “already flew up” in grocery stores last December, no longer rose sharply from the previous high base.
Nonetheless, consumers are obviously shocked to see that items purchased well below nine thousand forints last year now cost more than ten thousand forints.
The daily basket in the surveyed hypermarkets exceeded the psychological threshold of ten thousand forints by at least 91 forints.
And the highest value of the basket was 10,573 forints.
(In 2003, this value was 6,800 forints.)
Prices for Unicum and live fish have remained at almost last year's level, however prices for turkey net, nuts and poppy have risen sharply.
In the stores, the price of flour and bread followed the data of the KSH (Central Institute of Statistics) but, in Auchan, bread of one kilo was found at only 139 forints.
Competition did not lower the price of the product below 200 forints.
It was surprising to see, also in this hypermarket, that the price of the two-litre bottle of Coca-Cola was below 200 forints, so it cost only 257 forints per bottle included.
However, this year, in terms of daily shopping basket, Auchan was the most expensive and Cora the cheapest.
According to our calculations, Cora increased the price of its Daily Basket by 15 percent while Tesco and Auchan increased them by about 18 percent and 18 percent respectively.
When comparing last year’s most expensive basket and this year’s cheapest basket, we see a 12 percent gap while the difference between last year’s cheapest and this year’s most expensive basket is 21 percent.
Prices increased by an average of 1,480 forints.
Last year, prices rose by an average of 1,206 forints, while knowing that the impact of the increase in the VAT rate was already noticeable in last year's Christmas prices.
This process perplexed trade, and hypermarkets could not clearly determine what margin to apply to products as they were unable to predict the impact of price change on consumption.
(If a trader miscalculates the rotation of a product, he may lose a large profit on the margin appropriate to the intensity of the trade.)
Because of the change in the VAT rate, the increase in daily basket prices has evolved so excessively that the most expensive basket was 1,720 forints higher than the value of 2006, while the difference between the cheapest baskets was only 844 forints.
This year, the difference was not so excessive as the value of the most expensive basket was 1,630 forints higher than last year and the prices of the least expensive basket also increased by 1,284 forints.
Moving closer to the two Christmas seasons, we saw a catastrophic increase in prices, in less than 20 months the prices of everyday consumer goods increased by more than 30 percent in hypermarkets.
(This does not necessarily confirm the KSH data: for some basic foods, the Statistical Institute found a price increase of more than 30 percent in 12 months.
This is the case, for example, with flour and eggs.)
According to the daily basket of the latter, this seems almost absurd since the price level of this product, already expensive last year, has increased by just over 10 percent compared to the base.
According to the indices, flour suppliers occupy a stronger position than egg suppliers because they have managed to get the sudden increase in prices also accepted by multinationals.
In the commercial gold triangle, hypermarkets do not complain, they consistently record good years.
According to our experiences, the majority of customers no longer look at prices in the three hypermarkets visited.
They buy everything in quantity, they take the long-preservation food by pallets.
On Wednesday morning important queues formed at the checkouts of the three hypermarkets as the number of customers increased sharply.
However, according to our information, turnover is less important in the province, many multinationals complain to survey companies that they do not even reach the expected turnover, not only for food but also for sustainable consumer goods.
Many hospitals save on disinfectants
This year, more than a thousand infections, caused mainly by the improper use of antibiotics, have been recorded in hospitals.
The hygienic conditions of the hospitals, the insufficient number of beds, the overworking of medical personnel do not help to block the infections, says the chief doctor of the National Center for Epidemiology.
Many hospitals are also saving on disinfectants
Not long ago, MRSA infection was diagnosed at the trauma department of János Hospital.
The antibiotic-resistant bacterium was detected in a man hospitalized after a serious accident.
The patient was isolated.
At the beginning of the year a similar infection occurred in the same place.
The injured person in a serious car accident was discharged from the hospital but soon after he had to return to the hospital due to an MRSA infection and, since then, doctors have been unable to perform a major operation because of the bacteria found in his body.
As of 10 December this year, 1,094 hospital infections generated by a multidrug-resistant pathogen have been reported to the National Hospital Surveillance System, said Karolina Böröcz, chief physician at the National Center for Epidemiology.
It is the number of infections caused by a multidrug-resistant pathogen that has actually been recorded in hospitals and for the rest we have no information.
About two-thirds of infections (683 infections) were caused by MRSA, i.e. methicillin-oxacillin-resistant staphylococcus aureus.
A third of people carry Staphylococcus aureus (SA) bacteria in their noses without it developing a disease.
Infections caused by SA (such as angina, tonsillitis, skin infections, traumatic infections) respond well to antibiotics, they are easily curable.
However, if antibiotics are used excessively or inappropriately, the bacterium, which reacts well to antibiotics, will develop a bacterium well resistant to antibiotics that will proliferate quickly in poor hospital conditions.
In case of temporary or prolonged malfunction of the immune system, this bacterium can cause serious hospital infections, such as traumatic infection or sepsis, in elderly patients, with low weights or with a weakened organism.
According to the managing physician of the János hospital, there is nothing special about MRSA infections, these infections are part of the daily life of hospitals.
One should not confuse the infection with the epidemic, one does not find MRSA only or one does not seek them, said Tibor Nyulasi.
SAs are resistant to antibiotics.
“These patients are isolated, the caregivers put on rubber gloves and protective masks and we have antibiotics adapted to treat them,” said Tibor Nyulasi.
A priori, hospitalized patients are examined for MRSA, but infection cannot always be prevented.
Sampling is not fashionable
The vast majority of infections caused by MRSA could be prevented, but current conditions and circumstances in Hungarian hospitals are not favorable for preventing the development and proliferation of multidrug-resistant pathogens, says Karolina Böröcz.
As this infection manifests itself mainly in hospitals and seniors’ residences, hospitals should monitor hospitalized patients and immediately isolate patients with MRSA.
However, microbiological sampling is not fashionable in Hungarian hospitals.
It should be noted that the National Social Security Fund does not fund these reviews.
Most cases only emerge if the MRSA infection is detectable on the patient, said the chief physician of the epidemiological center.
The European Union has rigorous recommendations on the appropriate use of antibiotics in human medicine and there are Hungarian guidelines also for the cure of certain infections and syndromes.
Efforts must be made to ensure that antibiotic therapy is targeted, i.e. microbiological tests should be carried out to prevent drug resistance, but hospitals do not always take this into account.
Microbiological sampling is even rarer in ambulatory and basic care, said Karolina Böröcz.
Many hospitals save on disinfectants
Scientific evidence shows that MRSAs proliferate from one patient to another most often through medical staff.
It is therefore essential to wash your hands, put on gloves and protective masks, but important gaps are also detected in hospitals in this area.
MRSAs proliferate through droplet inhalation and contact infection, however, due to conditions in Hungarian hospitals, the contaminated patient cannot always be isolated.
In addition, the rooms are often full, the beds are often too close to each other, while in the event of an epidemic, the patients should be at least 1.5 meters away from each other.
Unfortunately, we also find that hospitals, in a difficult financial situation, are saving on disinfectants, they lack nurses, the sick are numerous, so the risk of contamination is even greater, said Karolina Böröcz.
According to Karolina Böröcz, in hospitals where preventive measures are followed, the number of infections is demonstrably lower or the proliferation of the pathogen can be blocked.
Government Project Against MRSA
The treatment of MRSA is an exorbitant expense for social security funds, which is why it is being fought everywhere.
In England, for example, the government has established a program to prevent or reduce the incidence of MRSA.
According to published data, this program is effective and MRSA infections show a decreasing trend in England.
The European Centre for Disease Prevention and Control (ECDC) has identified the prevention of the incidence of multidrug-resistant pathogens (such as MRSA) as one of its priorities, as well as the prevention of hospital infections caused by these pathogens.
The commissioner, who was the perpetrator of a fatal accident, was not in a state of drunkenness.
The official statement relating to the fatal accident caused by the Commissioner of the 22nd arrondissement has been drawn up.
It can be ruled out that the commissioner of the 22nd arrondissement, who has resigned from his post since crushing a pedestrian by causing his death last Tuesday, would have driven in a state of drunkenness or dizziness, said Friday Attila Morvai, spokeswoman of the Public Prosecutor's Office of the capital after the relative finding was established.
The finding confirmed the first result of the investigation which already found that the former commissioner had not consumed alcohol before he got behind the wheel
Last Tuesday, the former head of the police station of the 22nd arrondissement crushed a 55-year-old man who found himself facing him when he turned, with his personal car, in Kossuth Lajos street of the 22nd arrondissement.
(Furthermore, the fact that he was crossing the road outside the pedestrian crossing is not a mitigating circumstance, according to the Highway Code a car that starts a turn must let pedestrians pass.)
The pedestrian died after being transported to the hospital.
As a result of this accident, the Commissioner resigned from his position and requested his retirement because, according to the police communication, this accident greatly upset him.
The investigation into this case is conducted by the Budapest Prosecutor's Office.
Attila Morvai also mentioned that the former commissioner cooperated from the beginning with the magistrates responsible for conducting the investigation.
An additional €400 million for infrastructure
János Veres, Hungarian Finance Minister, and Marta Gajecka, Vice-President of the European Investment Bank (EIB), signed three agreements worth a total of €400 million in Budapest on a credit line to support education, transport and environment infrastructure and energy.
In 2006, the European Investment Bank (EIB) adopted a budget of EUR 300 million for the Hungarian budgetary financing of transport and environment projects to be carried out from the Cohesion Fund. A credit agreement worth EUR 100 million has already been signed by the parties. This time, the signed contract concerns the use of the remaining EUR 200 million.
The €150 million appropriation agreement also concerns the budgetary financing of education-related projects.
The EIB has approved a total of EUR 300 million for Hungary, with the remaining EUR 150 million to be used later, following the extension of the credit agreement.
The parties have signed a contract of 50 million euros for innovation, the state budget will use this envelope in the first place as part of the research and development project to be carried out at the University of Debrecen.
During the negotiations, the project of metro line 4 was also discussed.
The parties agreed that they would re-discuss the possible modification of the initial contract once Hungary has finalised the details of the subway financing with the EU.
According to János Veres, this could be done in the first quarter of 2008.
Since 1990, the EIB has allocated a total of EUR 8.4 billion to finance 113 projects in Hungary.
The EIB grants its loans according to the interest rate linked to EURIBOR, with a grace period of 8 years and without commitment fees.
Bulgaria, the EU’s real estate market paradise
The development of the Bulgarian real estate market is spectacular, the attention of all Europe is turned to this country of the Balkans little mentioned in the past.
What, or and who bought on this EU market that is always the cheapest but will quickly become expensive?
Analysis of the Bulgarian division of Re/Max.
Currently, in real estate, Bulgaria is unquestionably the most fashionable target in Eastern Europe with its ski apartments and cheap seaside houses.
In the mountains, the most popular regions are Bansko, Borovec, Pamprovo and Vitosa and, by the sea, Albena, the "Golden Sands", the "Sun Coast", the former Sozopol and Nessebar but they are increasingly looking for a building in the area of Kavarna and Balcik as well.
According to analysts of Re/Max Bulgaria, sooner or later, the central region of the country, namely Veliko Tarnovo, Gabrovo, Elena, Triavna, will also arouse the interest of investors and they are also increasingly numerous to buy in the very cheap corner of Ruse.
Sofia, the capital, also offers attractive opportunities, with retail and office spaces promising the highest depreciation rate.
Bulgaria is on its way to becoming one of the most attractive golf paradises in Europe and thus being a priority destination, after the summer season and the winter season, also in the other two seasons of the year.
More vigilant investors are already buying in large numbers, for example in the corner of Bansko.
According to analysts, people buying a building in Bulgaria are also looking to change their lives, their way of life.
Most of the buyers are English but others are coming from France, Belgium, Spain and more and more from Romania.
Maltese and Cypriot investors are also present. On the shores of the Black Sea and in the most renowned ski resorts, we traditionally meet many Russian buyers.
Foreign buyers are divided into three groups, says Georgij Jankov, Regional Director of Re/Max Bulgaria.
People who plan to settle buy renovated buildings, at a price ranging from 50 to 100 thousand euros, or old dilapidated houses, at a price ranging from 5 to 15 thousand euros, which are then renovated.
The criteria are easy access and communication possibilities, proximity to a large city, shops and in general that of the local doctor.
The second group includes buyers of second homes (since last December, Bulgaria has been listed among the top 10 holiday destinations in Germany).
The third group is made up of commercial investors who buy in the hope of achieving medium- to long-term added value.
The price of the capital's buildings is constantly rising as a result of an ever-increasing demand.
In the European Union, property prices are the lowest in Bulgaria. However, in the last 5 years, they have increased by 21 percent each year.
The increase in real estate prices essentially exceeds the increase in wages.
Fodor and the six percent Hungarians
According to the communication of Gábor Fodor, Minister of the Environment and Waters, the meetings of the professionals end on Tuesday, however, Wednesday, after the official opening, the negotiations of the ministers on the international climate regime after 2012 will continue.
Experts and politicians arriving from 192 countries around the world will discuss the Bali Roadmap, which is supposed to define efforts to be made after the Kyoto Protocol emission reduction period through 2012.
At the moment, there is a lively discussion on this between developing and developed countries.
The United States also reported that, for the time being, it did not want to discuss accurate figures, although it was willing to sign an agreement on reducing greenhouse gas emissions by 25 to 40 percent by 2020 from the 1990 level.
Another important topic of the conference is whether developed countries are committed to providing financial and technological assistance to countries in need, excluding emissions reductions.
An agreement was also signed on aid to be provided to developing countries.
The aid fund defined by the Kyoto Protocol will be managed by a 16-member board of directors, probably within the framework of the UN Global Environment Facility (GEF), Piac és Profit (Market and Profit) said.
Six percent of Hungary
On behalf of Hungary, Gábor Fodor, Minister for the Environment and Waters, confirms the EU's ambition to maintain its flagship role in global efforts to protect the climate and to encourage the signing of the new international agreement before 2009.
The minister explained that the EU is committed to reducing its greenhouse gas emissions by 20 per cent by 2020 from the level reached in 1990, regardless of the successful signing of the "Post 2012 Agreement", and is ready to reduce them by up to 30 per cent if other major regions of the world and/or developing countries are also ready to make commitments tailored to their responsibility and capabilities.
Gábor Fodor recalled that in 1997, the countries signatory to the Kyoto Protocol had targeted a total reduction of 5.2 per cent and all 15 EU members of that time made the commitment of 8 per cent less.
Hungary has made a commitment to reduce greenhouse gas emissions by 6 per cent compared to the level of the period between 1985 and 1987, our country will fulfill its commitment, recalls the press release of the Ministry of the Environment.
The stakes are high in Bali because the long-term international agreement on climate policy must be put in place within two years, otherwise the entry into force of the agreement would certainly be postponed after 2012. In this case, the commitments of reduction below the UN body-loaded values in the Kyoto Protocol would not be immediately followed by a new international system of reduction of emissions, the international IPCC report of which the need has been underlined in the new IPCC report.
The reduction in emissions would be delayed and the increase in the average temperature of the Earth by more than 2 degrees celcius could no longer be avoided, which scientists say would have extremely serious and irrevocable consequences.
The British Army Recruits on YouTube
The British military units communicate, on the video sharing site, recordings made during its operations in Iraq and Afghanistan with the aim of becoming popular.
First, it was the British Air Force (RAF) that became passionate about YouTube: special units operating in Afghanistan upload video footage of operations against the Taliban since March 2006, the BBC announced.
These recordings, taken using miniature cameras mounted on the helmet, are checked at the Air Force Operations Headquarters in Kandahar and then transferred to London or uploaded by compatriots on the Internet.
The political message is inescapable
Air force soldiers have already passed 139 sequences on the net by this route and their "chain" has been watched by more than 75,000 people.
The British Ministry of Defence registered as "defenseheadquarters" in the spring of 2007 and it is sharing videos on operations in Iraq and Afghanistan while the Commonwealth Office and the International Peacekeeping Forces in Iraq (MNFI) also have their own YouTube channels.
Mission to Afghanistan
According to the original objective of the air force, the videos were passed on the net to recruit, and according to the Ministry of Defence, they were also used to make known to the general public the real objectives of the army's presence abroad.
The propaganda published in this way costs almost nothing compared to the usual recruitment advertisements on television, Gordon Mackenzie, a defence consultant, told the BBC, but it also inevitably carries a political message because it justifies in a special form the merits of military operations decided by the government.
The Americans played a game.
The army is annoyed because, apart from the carefully composed and censored videos, amateur videos are posted on the sharing site that also feature, for example, the death of soldiers: in the somewhat hypocritical “official” propaganda films, officers do not avoid talking about the losses but they never present the bloody side of the fight.
In fact, many videos had already been posted on the net showing the areas of operations in Iraq and Afghanistan that were being carried out on a real mission, but the British army has only recently been busy loading these videos.
The Americans do the recruitment a little differently using the shooting game America's Army downloadable for free. In this game the player can put himself directly in the place of the soldiers as part of a more or less real simulation.
