The party is not marked in red everywhere
In Hungary, the law defines holidays exactly and around the holidays, it has become common to reorganize working days whose number will decrease next year.
The holidays are not uniform in the EU and the United States either.
Hungarian legislation distinguishes between national and state holidays as well as rest days.
Rest days are often linked to religious holidays or important historical events.
In Hungary, we celebrate the New Year, the last day of the year that ends and the first day of the New Year are also days of rest, the latter all the more so that the New Year's people can rest quietly.
In one year, we will have eleven festivals marked in red.
March 15 is a national day, in commemoration of the revolution of 1848, as well as October 23, which is the day to commemorate the 1956 revolution.
On August 20, we celebrate the constitution of our state, May 1st is Labor Day and on November 1st and 2nd, we remember our deceased family members and friends.
In addition, we have two days at Easter, Pentecost and Christmas.
The days of our state, national or religious holidays rarely falling on a weekend, according to the calendar, it has become common to reorganize working days in cases where there is only one working day left before or after the holiday marked in red.
It is true that we pay the price of extended weekends by working or going to school on the Saturday preceding the extended weekend.
For many years, the Minister of Labour has ruled in a special regulation on the days of replacement of the days before or after the holidays.
The Act extends to all employers and their employees, civil servants and persons working in the public service.
It does not, however, apply to service companies, institutions operating without interruption and in service, because of their vocation, and also for days of rest.
This year, working days will be changed only around the end of the year holidays: from December 24, life stops almost all over the country because according to experiences the majority of people rather work overtime or take vacations that they have saved for these purposes to be able to spend the days between Christmas and New Year's Day at home.
Next year many holidays fall in the middle or at the end of the week, so there will be fewer changes in working days compared to this year.
The schedule will be reorganized for the first time around Labor Day to allow employees to stay at home for four days in a row.
Saturday, April 25, will be a working day to have a day of rest on Friday, May 2.
Another change is planned for October 23rd: Saturday, October 18th will be a working day replacing Friday, October 24th.
On the other hand, next year, the end of the year is announced under the sign of the holidays because from December 24, everyone will take a non-stop break even if New Year's Day falls on a Wednesday.
Six Futile Things That Can Worry Colleagues Terribly
Emails we forget to send, voice messages we never receive, innocent lies that annoy us almost more: these are things that “beautify” the daily life of a workplace.
The question is whether we get used to these problems or take up the challenge and consciously avoid ambiguous situations, causing trouble to others.
Examples.
“Excuse me, I forgot to tell you that you were called from the marketing department,” a colleague tells you.
That you missed a date?
At best he is sorry and tries to fix things by calling the marketing department to tell them that he forgot to pass the message (this is the least common solution).
In most cases, the thing is arranged with excuses.
Before you have any painful explanations, it is useful to think about how you can cause unpleasant moments to your colleagues and make efforts to avoid them.
Are you borrowing something that doesn't belong to you?
There’s nothing more annoying than wanting to take a file, an office tool, or the phone and you can’t find them anywhere.
Remember the day before you put the stapler on the desk but it disappeared the next morning?
Are you accidentally finding your pen that you thought was lost on your colleague's desk?
Don't take anything from your colleagues without asking, or they're right to be angry at you for having stolen their property.
Don’t bring envelopes, post-it in your pocket because it can be annoying that there aren’t any more envelopes and you need them right away.
Are you talking about co-workers' privacy?
There are no good ways to stop gossip spreading.
Who did what, with whom?
Or and why?
Don’t tell everyone your information (suppositions) about your colleagues’ privacy!
If a colleague shares his intimate secrets with you, don’t abuse his trust!
Bury the shared information in yourself and do not discuss it with your colleagues in its absence even if your colleagues are also aware of it.
Do you claim to be sick for no good reason?
When you call the office and declare yourself sick under the pretext of a heartbreaking headache because you feel bad or you feel you need rest that day, think about the fact that your work, your urgent affairs, your term assignments must be done by someone else in your place.
Don't bother your colleagues!
If you know in advance that the next day you will not go to work or that something can happen that would force you to stay at home, do not forget to tell your boss and colleagues to avoid them being surprised by your absence the next day.
Smiling, Smiling, Phone
Are you diving into your work, but the laughter of your co-workers gets you out of it?
Did you unintentionally witness a phone conversation that you would have better not listen to?
Don’t bother your colleagues with buzzing, chanting, aloud chatting (which you lead over their heads), kicking, rude words, or loudly expressed discontent.
They can bother even if your colleagues are not immersed in a project (writing, design, organization).
Are you accusing others of a mistake?
If your work is not done by the deadline, you forget to send a letter or an important message, accuse no one for this forgetfulness!
Don’t put it on account of the eventual chaos in the office or your noisy colleagues!
Recognize it if you have made a mistake and if it has inconveniences for others, fix the fault!
Ask how you could fix your fault, fix the negligence!
Do you feel too at home in the office?
Putting on a jogging and slippers is comfortable at home but they are not suitable for the office!
Don’t put on comfortable jogging even if your function allows it!
Do not be neglected, respect your colleagues and yourself by dressing properly, and if your function requires it by putting on nice and elegant clothes, to go to work!
