Banks want to solve the crisis
The US Federal Reserve Bank, the European Central Bank and the British, Swiss and Canadian central banks have decided to fight the financial market crisis together.
More than $100 billion will be placed on the money markets through auctions.
It will be for the banks to sell, through an auction system, the interest rates at which they are willing to borrow money.
For example, the U.S. Fed will auction $40 billion and, in addition, it will provide $24 billion to the European and Swiss central banks.
This is the first time since the September 11 attacks that the Central Banks of Individual States have decided to take such concerted action, aimed at preventing or even reducing the effects of the financial crisis.
"This approach tends to solve the major problems of the economy, namely the growing lack of free capital that banks could lend," writes Bernard Baumohl in his report to clients of the consultancy Economic Outlook Group.
“The concerted action of the central banks has reduced the likelihood of a recession in the United States from 65 percent to about 50 percent,” Baumohl added in his report.
Banks have already lost $60 billion to unpaid loans, especially in the United States.
Analysts still expect further losses in billions.
"If the central banks have chosen this approach, it is that they have to really grasp what can still follow," said ABN Chief Economist Amro Kieran Davies.
"It seems that the situation is really bad," he added.
Central banks fear that if banks themselves have difficult access to loans, they will lend more to their customers.
This would reduce consumption and plunge the U.S. economy into a recession that could affect economic growth around the world.
The Central Banks made this choice after they failed to lower the interbank rate of Londres, called LIBOR, used to borrow on the interbank market.
This meant that banks were still concerned about mutual borrowing, despite the fact that the U.S., Canadian and English central banks repeatedly lowered their interest rates during the fall.
"It will have the same effect as a further drop in interest rates," Greg Salvaggio of Tempus Consulting told Reuters.
