Cuba, the most beautiful island in the Caribbean
For visitors, it is truly an island of freedom.
Everything you expect from your vacation can come true if you make a good choice.
Golden and white beaches like snow, high waves or a calm sea like a pond.
All-inclusive fins with waiters offering pizza, ice cream or intoxicating cocktails on the beach.
Kitesurfing, golf and roulette.
On the islands of the Caribbean Sea, you will not find this list only in its entirety, but enriched.
However, there is only one island on which you will find much more and it is Cuba, the largest and most beautiful island in the Greater Antilles.
In the time of the Spaniards, Cuba had been the stronghold of their invasion of America.
Christopher Columbus described it as the most beautiful place the human eye has ever seen.
Havana became the repository and place of transshipment of the treasures that the Spaniards had stolen and transported to Europe.
Then came the American era.
The Hotel Nacional was built in the early 20's.
It was Lucky Luciano, one of the leaders of the American mafia, who built it, since everything that was a crime in the US (especially under prohibition) was admitted and supported in Cuba: drugs, gambling, prostitution.
Among his clients were, among others,
Winston Churchill, Ava Gardner, Frank Sinatra.
In Havana, high-rise buildings grew and cars, belonging to the cult symbols of the 50's of the last century, circulated on the wide boulevards.
Ernest Hemingway bought a property in San Francisco de Paula, near Havana, and in Coj<0xC3><0xAD>mar he had his yacht.
Show business stars and politicians across America left their signatures on the walls of the Bodeguita del Medio.
What about today?
You can leave your autograph on the walls of the Havana Bodeguita.
In the bar of the Hotel Nacional, a luxury hotel, you can mix the cocktail of your choice.
And these cult cars still circulate in Havana, since the jigouli and the old imported fiat have already been rotten for a long time, in a climate so salty and humid.
Although Havana, especially the oldest part, is noticeably declining, nowhere else in the vicinity are there as many splendid colonial monuments as there are right there.
Other places become more beautiful, for example Trinidad.
Since tourism brings the money if necessary, its development has the green light.
In the last fifteen years, new hotels have grown not only in Havana, but especially in Varader, on the coast of the province Holgu<0xC3><0xAD>n, and also on the small islands such as Cayo Coco, Cayo Guillermo and others.
Cuba still offers a fantasy that is unique in the world and that will be appreciated especially by fans of small trains.
The cane had come back from the extended plantations in the sweets on a narrow lane by small steam and motor trains.
Their rolling stock has not been renewed for decades and this is how small locomotives can be seen in operation whose contemporaries are only in museums elsewhere.
Where to direct your footsteps?
The majority of visitors do not miss the best known places.
There is no need to write much about Varadero or Havana.
Otherwise remember that in the property of Hemingway, already mentioned, there is a museum and that whoever loves this writer should not miss the visit.
The valley of Vi<0xC5><0x88>ales to the west of the island is one of the most picturesque corners of Cuba.
Exuberant vegetation grows there on limestone soil.
Mogotes, limestone balloons and rocks rise candlelit from the bottom of the valley, and, having caught fertile earth in their bowels, even its rotten rocks are covered with a very dense vegetable carpet.
The valley is probably the place where Cuban tobacco of the best quality is grown.
The final shape of this product can be found if you visit one of the cigar factories in Havana.
Someone might also find it interesting that this is where the Chilean episode of Major Zeman was shot.
Trinidad (disambiguation)
An ancient city founded shortly after the Spanish colonized the island.
It was the slave trade and the sugar trade that brought him glory and wealth.
Wealth was embodied in the beauty and showcase city character of this small town.
Koloniáln<0xC3><0xAD> <0xC5><0xA1>pan<0xC4><0x9B>lská architektura,v<0xC3><0xBD>razn<0xC4><0x9B> ovlivn<0xC4><0x9B>ná pozd<0xC4><0x9B>j<0xC5><0xA1><0xC3><0xAD>mi francouzsk<0xC3><0xBD>mi osadn<0xC3><0xAD>ky, se za <0xC4><0x8D>ty<0xC5><0x99>i stalet<0xC3><0xAD> tém<0xC4><0x9B><0xC5><0x99> nezm<0xC4><0x9B>nila.
Trinidad, located between the sea and the Escambray mountain range, is so far apart that even in the 50's of the last century, there was no road that would connect this region with the rest of the country.
This isolation allowed him to stay on the sidelines.
We didn't build anything, and that's why we didn't demolish anything either, everyone was content to have a roof over their heads.
If you have more time in Trinidad than an afternoon, then it is worth seeing interesting places in the area, such as Playa Ancón Beach or the Sugar Valley.
Then, in the evening, it is customary to go to the Casa de la M<0xC3><0xBA>sica, which comes alive after sunset and where the music only gets quiet in the early morning.
Baracoa
Some refer to this town located in the far east of Cuba as the most beautiful of the island.
This opinion is certainly already influenced by the path that leads there.
The two roads that lead from Guantánamo must cross high and rugged mountains and cross a landscape almost without marks of human activity.
UNESCO has inscribed the eastern coffin of Cuba, thanks to its intact landscape, on the list of World Heritage Sites.
We make the best chocolate, in the church, there is the cross of Christopher Columbus (in reality, it was born about a hundred years after the journey of Columbus) and from the hill where stands the old castle and the current hotel El Castillo, we see several table mountains, the most famous of which is El Yunque.
About coffee, rum, cigars, the Sierra Maestra mountain range, the Bay of Sows and Isla de Pinos, the Tropicana cabaret, the sanctuary of the patron saint of Cuba Caridad del Cobre, the Santeria, the African religions practiced by the descendants of the former slaves, about all this one could fill a number of pages.
But, as they say, it is better to see once.
