According to the United States, the lack of troops and necessary equipment has an impact on the conduct of the mission in Afghanistan.
According to Defence Minister Robert Gates, NATO should outline a concrete plan for the coming years.
The mission in Afghanistan is not proceeding as it should, the representatives of the countries that have troops in the southern part of the country agreed in Edinburgh in Scotland.
In addition to the growing challenge on the part of the Taliban movement, the eight states involved are now also discussing future plans and the coordination of allies.
While the U.S. this week called on NATO troops through Defense Minister Robert Gates for greater activity, Britain sees strengthening Afghan government authority and intensifying development aid as a priority.
“Evolution in Afghanistan is perceptible, but military power can only be part of the solution.
The other is to allow the inhabitants to start a new development of the economy and security themselves," British Defense Minister Des Browne told the BBC.
Ninety percent
The activity of Afghan insurgents is, according to U.S. military data, the most intense in the last five years.
The number of violent actions increased 27 percent from last year, up to 60 percent in the southern Helmand province.
NATO countries have about 40,000 troops in Afghanistan, nearly a quarter of them in the southern part.
Now, according to the United States, the allies have reached their absolute limit and in the organization and equipment of the troops.
Concretely, they are asking for other helicopters, soldiers and experts for the training of Afghan troops.
“We will have to think seriously about the concrete goals for the coming period, as well as how to achieve them,” Gates said.
