Government Debt Will Rise to $1 Billion in 2009
The burden of a state debt exceeding 84,000 kronor falls on each Czech.
At the end of September, total debt rose to 842.7 billion crowns.
The government had planned to borrow 159.2 billion crowns this year.
As a result of better-than-expected savings in the state budget, the Ministry reduced the projected amount to 152.8 billion crowns.
The state debt of the Czech Republic rose towards the end of September to 842.7 billion kronor.
During the nine months of this year it increased by 40.2 billion crowns.
However, as of June, it has decreased by 13.4 billion crowns.
Today, the Ministry of Finance confirmed its state debt data from the beginning of October.
The burden of a debt exceeding 84,000 crowns falls on each Czech.
Over the past year, the state has borrowed more than 111 billion crowns.
"At the moment, it appears that, thanks to a smaller deficit planned for next year, we could cross the border by a trillion kroner only in 2009.
Next year, the debt is expected to be between 900 billion and one trillion crowns,” said Patria Finance analyst David Marek for the server iHNed.cz.
Next Finance analyst Vladim<0xC3><0xAD>r Pikor's forecast is similar: "We could exceed the trillion in 2009.
The exact date will depend on the next budget that is not yet known.
If it appeared that the situation on the political scene was changing, that policies were ready to save more, the date could be pushed back to 2010.
But I’m not expecting that change,” he said.
Debts are growing
The debt of the state is constituted by the debts of the central government and it is generated mainly by the accumulation of the deficits of the state budget.
Government debt is financed by treasury bonds, annuity bonds, direct borrowings or, for example, loans from the European Investment Bank.
The domestic debt of the state has so far increased this year from 38.5 billion to 719.4 billion crowns.
The foreign debt of the state has increased this year from 1.7 billion kronor to 123.3 billion kronor.
The so-called negotiable state debt reached 803.3 billion crowns at the end of September and as of June it decreased by 13.7 billion crowns.
The average debt payability of the state was 6.5 years.
“Total debt increased year-on-year from the first to the third half of the year by 13 percent, which, given the current good health of the economy, is far too high.
Interestingly, the increase is mainly generated by annuity securities where it reaches 20 percent.
It is bad that the debt is growing, but on the other hand it indicates that there will be matter to be negotiated when pension reform comes,” Pikora said.
Better than we expected
It follows from the government's 2007 debt financing and management strategy, which the government had planned to borrow 159.2 billion crowns this year.
At the beginning of September, thanks to a better-than-expected evolution of savings in the state budget, the ministry reduced the planned amount to 152.8 billion crowns.
The sum is essentially made up of the deficit in the state budget, which will clearly reach 76 billion crowns this year, instead of the originally planned 91.3 billion crowns.
Secondly, these are the maximum sources foreseen for the Czech Consolidation Agency, namely 13.3 billion kronor, the 10 billion reserve for pension payments, the financing of state annuity securities for 43 billion kronor and the repayments of European Investment Bank loans amounting to 1.8 billion kronor.
She appeared before a court in Khartoum today for naming a teddy bear
The British teacher tried in Sudan for insulting Islam was sentenced Thursday night by a court in Khartoum to 15 days in prison and deportation, her lawyer said.
The British woman was accused of letting pupils aged 6-7 give the name Muhammad to a teddy bear while any depiction of the prophet of Islam is illegal.
She was punished with a lash.
The 54-year-old British schoolteacher at Unity High School in Khartoum, Sudan, was arrested at her home on Sunday and charged with breaching Islam and sedition, under Article 125 of the Sudanese Criminal Code, following several complaints from parents of pupils to the Sudanese Ministry of Education.
The story actually goes back to September, when this teacher asked her pupils, aged 6/7, to choose a name for the teddy bear in the class.
“Eight names come out of the mouths of children, including Hassan, Abdullah and Mohammed,” said school principal Robert Boulos.
Finally, after a vote in the classroom, 20 out of 23 children chose Mohamed as their preferred first name.
Mohamed is of course the name of the Muslim prophet, but above all a very common name in Sudan.
The children then made a book for the class with the photo of the bear followed by the caption "My name is Mohamed".
The bear itself did not carry any labels with that name, but the problem is simply that of the depiction of the prophet considered an insult to Islam.
One of Gillian Gibbons' Muslim colleagues, a teacher at the same school in Sudan, said he knew her well and that she would never have done anything that could be insulting to a religious faith, "I just regret that she asked the children to vote for a name," according to him, it is only an "innocent mistake."
Opinion shared by many of the teacher's students who describe her as "very caring towards her students" and "who never talks about religion in class".
Remember that the first name Mohamed is also the second most given first name in Britain, it is written in English in 14 different ways.
This name often chosen by Muslim families is a way of honoring the prophet (often given to the first child in a family).
But what are the rules regarding the use of this name?
Can you give it to a toy?
This is, of course, a matter of interpretation.
They did not reach an agreement on the future status of the province on Wednesday at the last negotiating session in Vienna.
In the end, failure.
Kosovo Serbs and Albanians concluded a sixth and final session on Wednesday morning in Baden, Austria, without having been able to overcome their differences on the future status of the separatist province.
"It is unfortunate that the parties have not been able to reach an agreement on the status," European Ombudsman Wolfgang Ischinger said at a press conference in Vienna.
Stressing that peace in the region was “at stake,” his US counterpart, Frank Wisner, urged Belgrade and Pristina to abide by their commitments to preserve peace and dialogue beyond the end of negotiations.
“There are no immediate plans for violence, but we are entering a very difficult period,” he added, noting that “obvious tensions exist.”
End of mediation on December 10
The mediators of the troika, which includes the European Union, the United States and Russia, will visit Serbia and Kosovo for the last time on Monday.
The future of the 90 percent Albanian-speaking province could become clearer when Ischinger, Wisner and Russian mediator Alexander Botsane-Khartchenko submit their report to the UN Security Council by 10 December.
The talks in Baden, near Vienna, were the sixth and final negotiating session since the troika was tasked with a new mediation by the United Nations last August.
Americans and Europeans expect their mediation to end on December 10.
The Russians, who have already blocked the Security Council from granting independence in Kosovo, insist on continuing negotiations beyond this deadline.
“Russia was and remains committed to a negotiated solution, a compromise solution,” Botsane-Khartchenko said.
The unilateral declaration of independence?
After eight years of UN administration of Kosovo, Westerners believe that independence under EU supervision is the only viable solution.
Pristina is ready to proclaim it unilaterally if the Security Council does not decide in its favour.
Belgrade insists on greater autonomy.
"Unfortunately, no agreement has been reached," said the president of the Kosovo Autonomous Authority, Fatmir Sejdiu, in the hotel in Baden where the "last chance negotiations" had been taking place since Monday.
Hashim Thaci, former commander of the Kosovo rebellion and future prime minister of the province, expressed his regrets.
But he added that Belgrade’s autonomy plan “belongs to a past that has led to murders and deportations.”
‘Domino effect’
Serbian President Boris Tadic said a compromise was still feasible, warning the Albanian majority of Kosovo against the consequences of a unilateral proclamation of the province's independence.
