A heavy memory
After more than 60 years of secrecy, the Nazi archives of Bad Arolsen, which trace the fate of 17.5 million victims of the Hitler regime, are open to access.
The 47 million archival documents, stored on 27 km of linear in Bad Arolsen (Hesse), were until now only consultable for a "humanitarian" purpose, that is to say individually and by name, at the request of a former victim or his beneficiaries.
The eleven states in charge of their management - including Germany, France, Israel and the United States - agreed in May 2006 to open them to researchers and historians.
Since the ratification process of this agreement by all States has been completed, the opening has been effective since yesterday.
Sensitive information
Historians’ access to Bad Arolsen will allow them to carry out research “in particular on the displacement of prisoners, the population of camps and the state of health of forced workers,” says Reto Meistern, the director of the archives managed by the International Committee of the Red Cross (ICRC).
Until recently, several States, including Germany, had opposed the opening to the public of such naming documents, because of the sensitive nature of certain information.
Such as the alleged homosexuality or the mental disability of some victims of deportation.
The records of the concentration camps or the arrest warrants established by the Gestapo had been collected after the war for a practical purpose: to find the deported civilians or subject to compulsory labour and, if necessary, to provide them with proof of their internment, in order to pave the way for their compensation.
Even today in Bad Arolsen, more than 300 permanent employees process tens of thousands of individual applications.
However, for some of the scientific community, access to Bad Arolsen is of limited interest.
“There is nothing fundamentally new to expect from these documents,” said Professor Wolfgang Benz, director of the Center for Research on Antisemitism at the Technische Universität Berlin in 2006.
