The new gas deal between Russia and Ukraine raises the alarm.
A dispute over the price of gas between Ukraine and Russia is fermenting, thus increasing the risk of repercussions on fuel exports to Europe.
Most Russian gas exports to the European Union (EU) are conveyed through pipelines, and each pipeline is scrupulously monitored.
Kiev has announced that if Russia increases the cost of fuel, it will increase transit taxes to Russia.
Last year, an altercation between the two had caused a decrease in supplies to the EU countries.
The latest dispute between Kiev and Moscow comes after the Ukrainian government and Gazprom, Russia’s gas-supplying monopoly company, tried in vain to find an agreement on the cost of Russian gas supplied to Ukraine for the year 2008.
Gazprom said it would increase its prices to Ukraine as expected, given that it agreed to pay for 2008, up to 50% more for the supply of gas from neighboring Turkmenistan.
Analysts said this would mean for Ukraine a 40% increase in import costs from Gazprom.
"It is essential for us to use all our arguments during the talks, remembering that we are a country through which most of the gas passes," Ukraine's economy minister Anatoly Kinkh told Reuters.
Fluctuations in gas costs are likely to be linked to our discussions about transit taxes (to Western Europe) via Ukraine.
The last major altercation between Moscow and Kiev caused the interruption of supplies of Gazprom to Ukraine in January 2006.
This led to a drop in exports to Western Europe, which increased prices.
Russian gas accounts for a quarter of the European Union's supplies.
Russia has the largest stockpiles of gas, although most of them are still underdeveloped.
As a result, Gazprom supplements its own supplies with gas from Turkmenistan and other nations of the former Soviet Union in Central Asia.
