Venus is the infernal twin of Earth.
Despite its hostile atmosphere to life, Venus is more Earth-like than previously thought: the European spacecraft Venus Express has discovered lightning bolts in the atmosphere and swirls of wind at the poles, similar to those that appear in the winter on Earth.
For almost three decades, scientists have assumed that there are lightning bolts on Venus.
The European probe "Venus Express" has today provided proof of this - it detected electromagnetic waves at the edge of the atmosphere: Lightning on Venus bursts at a height of about 56 kilometers of cloud-to-cloud, reports Christopher Russell of the University of California, Los Angeles, in the scientific magazine "Nature".
According to the famous theory of cyprine, lightning would have caused life to appear on Earth: the storm would have stimulated reactions in the oceans that led to the formation of amino acids, the cornerstone of life.
This is not the case on Venus: “If there was life, it must have been at a very early date in history,” explains Sean Solomon of the Carnegie Institution in Washington.
There are hardly any living things on the surface of Venus today: the atmosphere is about a hundred times denser than on Earth, there are sometimes temperatures of 500 degrees.
“Venus may be the hellish twin of Earth, but it remains a twin,” Russell said.
Why Venus, which resembles Earth so much in mass and dimensions, has been struck by such a different evolution, is the fundamental question of the ASE mission.
The departure of "Venus Express" in November 2005 was an important milestone in Venusian research, since no probes had been on their way to explore this planet since the 1990s.
In the opinion of the researchers, the most recent research results that have now been presented in several articles of "Nature" do not only highlight the singularity of Venus within the solar system.
They also show that the commonalities with the Earth of our neighboring planet are more numerous than assumed at first.
Thus the researchers found, in addition to the wind swirls already known at the north pole, a swirl of clouds at the south pole, which rotates even faster.
The phenomenon is reminiscent of air currents in the hemispheres in winter, writes a team of researchers around Giuseppe Piccioni of the Italian Istituto di Astrofisica Spaziale e Fisica Cosmica.
The second planet in the solar system has almost the same mass as Earth and is, with a diameter of 12,100 kilometers, almost as large.
The planet called the evening or morning star revolves around the sun in just 225 days.
However, it turns much slower on itself: a Venusian day lasts 243 Earth days.
Although Venus, with surface temperatures of 460 degrees Celsius and a pressure of 92 bar, is hardly reminiscent of Earth, scientists assume that the two planets formed under similar conditions.
On both, water accumulated and remained on Earth in the form of oceans, but was lost in space on Venus.
And while carbon dioxide has settled on Earth as carbonate, it makes up most of the atmosphere on Venus.
