These aren't Warhols' crates.
The one who connects the concepts Sweden and wooden case, thinks of Ikea, but not of Andy Warhol.
Or is it?
At the moment, wooden crates made in Sweden cast shadows on Warhol’s list of works.
Much of the ninety "Type Stockholm" Brillo-Boxes listed there are counterfeits.
After the Swedish newspaper "Expressen" questioned a few months ago the authenticity of Andy Warhol's Brillo-Boxes of the year 1968, the internal research of the Moderna Museet in Stockholm today culminates in a disenchanting result: the six "Brillo-Boxes", of which the former director of the Pontus Hulten museum gifted in 1995 the "Moderna-Boxes" on the international market, as well as the "Moderna-Museum"
The ancient history is entangled, a bewildering sequence of artistic and curatorial productions.
In 1964, Warhol created in New York his first "Brillo-Boxes", painted wooden boxes, which are based on the red-blue-white design of the powdered soap boxes "Brillo".
An exhibition of his work at the Moderna Museet presented in 1968 - with Warhol's agreement - hundreds of Brillo boxes made of cardboard: These did not come (for financial reasons) from Warhol, but had been delivered directly from the Brillo cartoning factory.
These were not works of art here, but rather their models, exhibition samples.
At the same time, Warhol had given permission in 1968 to produce some Brillo wooden crates in Sweden, which were not exhibited at the Moderna Museet.
Witnesses at the time speak today of about fifteen wooden crates that at the time would have entered the history of art and auctions, as authorized original Brillo-Boxes of Andy Warhol, with the appellation "Type Stockholm".
Some of them reached more than $100,000 in auctions.
The problem now is that the legendary director of the Pontus Hultén Museum erroneously claimed later that about a hundred wooden crates had been produced and exhibited in Sweden in 1968, which Warhol later sold to him.
In fact, the 105 Hulten boxes were produced in Malmö in 1990 alone, for an exhibition in St. Petersburg.
By that time, Warhol had already died for three years.
Lars Byström, chief curator of the Moderna Museet, examined, alongside the museum's six Brillo-Boxes, three other private Swedish collections, two of which were made in Stockholm in 1968: their laminated panels were first printed and sanded, then applied with a brush of white oil paint.
The texture of the copies dating back to 1990 reveals, on the contrary, that the paint was applied directly without a backing layer on the laminated panels, using a paint roller - moreover, it is not an oil painting, but an acrylic.
"These crates have not been authorized by the artist and should be removed from the official list of Andy Warhol's Brillo-Boxes," says Moderna Museet director Lars Nittve: "If the 'Andy Warhol Art Authentication Board' in New York does not come up with another decision, the Moderna Museet will classify its six crates in the collection."
Already in July the Authentication Board announced, of course, that it would investigate the "heavy accusations" that will be raised in the case of boxes of powdered soap.
But since then there is an inexorable silence there.
